	<div data-role="header" role="banner">
		<h2>Priority Dashboard</h2>
	</div>
	<div data-role="content" role="main">
		<h2>What do I do?</h2>
		<p>The "Priority Dashboard" is your way of instantly seeing what needs to be done, and what is most important. This is really nothing more than our master issue tracker.</p>
		  <a href="http://redmine.fireworksproject.com/projects/fireworks/issues" data-role="button" data-theme="e" data-icon="arrow-r" data-iconpos="right" target="_blank">Go to the Priority Dashboard</a>
	</div>
</div><!-- #priority_dashboard_overview -->

<div id="project_management_overview" data-role="page" data-theme="a">
	<div data-role="header" role="banner">
		<h2>Project Management</h2>
	</div>
	<div data-role="content" role="main">
		<p>Of course project management is important in any organization, and we're no different. In our case, because we are a virtual company, we keep a repository of assets with every project we manage. These assets may include documents or images, but almost always include source code for a software project.</p>

		<div data-role="collapsible" data-collapsed="true" data-theme="b">
			<h3>Primary PM tool: Github</h3>

			<p>The assets of our projects are the core of their existence. So, for project management we've chosen a tool that is capable of managing our digital assets well: <a href="http://github.com/">Github</a>, the web based source control and project mangement service.</p>

			<p>Many of you may know Github as a popular code hosting service for open source software projects, but it also works very well as a generalized project management tool. This is especially true for us, because we need to keep versioned repositories of project assets like documentation, content, and source code all in the same place.</p>

		  <a href="http://github.com/FireworksProject" data-role="button" data-theme="e" data-icon="arrow-r" data-iconpos="right" target="_blank">Go to Github</a>
		</div>

		<div data-role="collapsible" data-collapsed="true" data-theme="b">
			<h3>The Skunk Works.</h3>

			<p>However, projects do not begin in Github. Before that, they are incubated within a project management system we call the "<a href="#skunk_works_overview">Skunk Works</a>", which is a <a href="http://www.redmine.org/">Redmine</a> deployment. After a project has reached a milestone, it becomes an "official" project and is moved into Github.</p>

			<p>With the Skunk Works -&gt; Github workflow we're able to make a mess first, and then clean it up when we think we might be on to something good. The goal is to promote a practice of creative freedome that will make great ideas into a reality.</p>

		  <a href="http://redmine.fireworksproject.com/" data-role="button" data-theme="e" data-icon="arrow-r" data-iconpos="right" target="_blank">Go to the Skunk Works</a>
		</div>
	</div>
</div><!-- #project_management_overview -->

<div id="general_discussion_overview" data-role="page" data-theme="a">
